window.__pages={"7674":"<h2>Closing an Insolvent Company Through a CVL</h2>\n\n<p>If the company cannot pay its debts and continuing to trade is no longer viable, a Creditors' Voluntary Liquidation (CVL) is the standard route for an orderly shutdown. Directors initiate the process, a licensed insolvency practitioner takes control of asset realisation, and the company is dissolved once creditors have been dealt with.</p>\n\n<p>This page covers the full CVL process: who qualifies, what it costs, how long it takes, and what directors face during and after the procedure. It is written for directors who have accepted that closure is necessary and need to understand the mechanics before instructing a practitioner.</p>\n\n<p>Delay matters. Trading while insolvent exposes directors to personal liability under the Insolvency Act 1986, and HMRC escalation (including winding-up petitions) can remove the option of a voluntary process entirely. The sooner a CVL is started, the more control directors retain over the outcome.</p>\n\n<h2>When a CVL Is Used</h2>\n\n<p>A CVL applies when the company is insolvent and the directors choose to wind it up voluntarily rather than waiting for a creditor to force the issue.</p>\n\n<p>Insolvency has two statutory tests under s.123 of the Insolvency Act 1986:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Cash-flow test:</strong> the company cannot pay its debts as they fall due. This includes tax liabilities, supplier invoices, loan repayments, and rent.</li>\n  <li><strong>Balance-sheet test:</strong> the company's total liabilities exceed its total assets, including contingent and prospective liabilities.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Failing either test is enough. Most CVLs are triggered by the cash-flow test, often after months of mounting HMRC arrears, failed payment plans, or creditor pressure that makes continued trading unsustainable. For a detailed breakdown of both tests, see the <a href=\"/insolvency-test/\">insolvency test guide</a>.</p>\n\n<p>Common triggers include HMRC Time to Pay refusals, bounce-back loan defaults, loss of a major customer, or a statutory demand that cannot be paid within 21 days. If a winding-up petition has already been filed, a CVL may still be possible but the window is narrow. Directors facing an active petition should seek immediate advice.</p>\n\n<h2>Who Can Use a CVL</h2>\n\n<p>Any UK limited company that is insolvent can enter a CVL, provided the directors and shareholders follow the statutory procedure.</p>\n\n<p>The key threshold is a shareholder vote. Under s.84(1)(b) of the Insolvency Act 1986, the shareholders must pass a special resolution to wind up the company voluntarily. That requires at least 75% of voting shareholders to approve.</p>\n\n<p>In practice, most companies entering a CVL are owner-managed, so the director and majority shareholder are the same person. The vote is a formality. Where there are multiple shareholders who disagree, the 75% threshold becomes a real constraint, and directors may need to negotiate or consider alternative routes.</p>\n\n<p>There is no minimum debt level, no minimum number of creditors, and no requirement that the company has traded for a specific period. Dormant companies with outstanding liabilities can also enter a CVL, though <a href=\"/company-strike-off-and-dissolution/\">strike-off</a> may be more appropriate if debts are negligible and no creditor is likely to object.</p>\n\n<h2>How the CVL Process Works Step by Step</h2>\n\n<p>The CVL follows a fixed statutory sequence. Directors cannot skip steps or change the order.</p>\n\n<h3>1. Board decision and insolvency practitioner appointment</h3>\n\n<p>The directors hold a board meeting and resolve that the company cannot continue trading due to its liabilities. At this stage, an insolvency practitioner (IP) is engaged. The IP must be licensed by a recognised professional body (IPA, ICAEW, ICAS, or the Insolvency Service). The IP will assess the company's position, prepare the necessary documents, and advise on timing.</p>\n\n<h3>2. Shareholder resolution</h3>\n\n<p>The shareholders pass a special resolution (75% majority) to wind up the company voluntarily. Under the Insolvency Rules 2016, this can be done by written resolution rather than a physical meeting, which speeds up the process for owner-managed companies.</p>\n\n<h3>3. Creditor notification and decision procedure</h3>\n\n<p>Within 14 days of the shareholder resolution, creditors must be given notice of the liquidation and invited to participate in a decision procedure. Since the Insolvency Rules 2016 replaced the old creditor meetings, this is typically handled by correspondence (a \"deemed consent\" procedure). Creditors can request a physical meeting, but this is uncommon in small-company CVLs.</p>\n\n<p>Creditors have the right to appoint a different liquidator if they choose, though in the majority of cases the IP proposed by the directors is confirmed.</p>\n\n<h3>4. Statement of affairs</h3>\n\n<p>The directors must prepare a statement of affairs: a verified document listing all assets, liabilities, and creditor details. This is sworn by the directors and filed with the liquidator. Inaccuracies or omissions in the statement of affairs can trigger investigation, so accuracy matters.</p>\n\n<h3>5. Liquidator takes office</h3>\n\n<p>Once appointed, the liquidator takes full control. Directors lose their powers. The liquidator's role is to realise assets, investigate the company's affairs, adjudicate creditor claims, distribute funds, and report on director conduct.</p>\n\n<h2>What Documents and Decisions Are Involved</h2>\n\n<p>Directors need to prepare or provide the following during the CVL process:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Board minutes</strong> recording the decision that the company is insolvent and should enter liquidation</li>\n  <li><strong>Special resolution</strong> of shareholders (75% majority) to wind up the company</li>\n  <li><strong>Statement of affairs</strong> listing all assets, liabilities, creditors (with addresses and amounts owed), and any security held by creditors</li>\n  <li><strong>Director questionnaires</strong> covering the company's trading history, reasons for insolvency, and any transactions that may require investigation</li>\n  <li><strong>Company books and records</strong> including management accounts, bank statements, VAT returns, and HMRC correspondence</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>The IP handles statutory filings with Companies House and the Insolvency Service, including the notice of appointment and the Forms 4.25 and 600 series under the Insolvency Rules 2016.</p>\n\n<p>Directors should expect to spend several hours compiling information. Incomplete records slow the process and increase costs, because the liquidator must reconstruct the company's financial position from bank statements and third-party records.</p>\n\n<h2>How Long a CVL Takes</h2>\n\n<p>From first contact with an IP to the liquidator taking office, the typical timeline is 10 to 21 days. That covers the board meeting, shareholder resolution, creditor notification period, and formal appointment.</p>\n\n<p>The full liquidation, from appointment to dissolution, depends on asset complexity. A simple case with no significant assets, no property, and straightforward creditor claims can be finalised in 6 to 12 months. Cases involving property sales, ongoing litigation, book debt collection, or HMRC disputes can take 12 to 24 months or longer.</p>\n\n<p>The statutory minimum before dissolution is approximately 3 months after the final account is sent to creditors and filed with Companies House. The company is then dissolved by the Registrar.</p>\n\n<h2>What a CVL Costs</h2>\n\n<p>CVL costs typically fall between 4,000 and 6,000 pounds plus VAT for a straightforward case with limited assets. More complex cases, especially those involving property, contested claims, or director conduct issues, cost more because the liquidator's time increases.</p>\n\n<p>The fee covers the IP's statutory duties: creditor notifications, asset realisation, investigations, reporting, and final dissolution. Disbursements (bonding, advertising, Companies House fees) are separate and typically add 500 to 1,000 pounds.</p>\n\n<h3>Redundancy funding: how directors can offset the cost</h3>\n\n<p>Directors who are also employees of the company (with a PAYE employment contract and a minimum of two years' continuous service) may be eligible to claim statutory redundancy pay from the Redundancy Payments Service (now part of the Insolvency Service). The claim is made after the liquidator is appointed.</p>\n\n<p>Statutory redundancy pay is calculated using age, length of service, and weekly pay (capped at the statutory weekly limit). For directors with long service, the payment can be several thousand pounds, which in many cases covers or exceeds the cost of the CVL itself.</p>\n\n<p>This is a legitimate entitlement under the Employment Rights Act 1996, not a loophole. The liquidator must confirm the director's employment status, and HMRC will check that the employment was genuine. Directors paid solely through dividends with no employment contract do not qualify.</p>\n\n<p>For more on eligibility, see the <a href=\"/liquidation/\">liquidation overview</a>, which covers redundancy in the context of the broader process.</p>\n\n<h2>What Happens Once the Process Starts</h2>\n\n<p>Once the liquidator is appointed, the company stops trading (if it has not already) and the liquidator takes control of all assets.</p>\n\n<h3>Asset realisation</h3>\n\n<p>The liquidator sells assets (equipment, vehicles, stock, intellectual property, debtor balances) and collects any money owed to the company. Property with secured charges is dealt with according to the security holder's rights. Unsecured assets are sold and the proceeds distributed to creditors in the statutory order: fixed charge holders, preferential creditors (employees and certain HMRC claims), floating charge holders, then unsecured creditors.</p>\n\n<h3>Creditor claims and distributions</h3>\n\n<p>Creditors submit proof of debt. The liquidator adjudicates each claim and, if there are sufficient funds, makes distributions according to the statutory hierarchy. In many small-company CVLs, unsecured creditors receive little or nothing because preferential claims and liquidation costs absorb the available funds.</p>\n\n<h3>Director conduct report</h3>\n\n<p>The liquidator is required to file a report on director conduct with the Insolvency Service (under s.7A of the Company Directors Disqualification Act 1986). This report covers whether directors traded responsibly, kept adequate records, filed statutory returns, and acted in creditors' interests once insolvency was known or suspected.</p>\n\n<p>The conduct report is not optional. Every CVL generates one. Directors who cooperated fully, ceased trading at an appropriate time, and maintained proper records have little to fear from this step. For more detail on what investigators look for, see the <a href=\"/what-happens-to-a-director-during-liquidation/\">director during liquidation guide</a>.</p>\n\n<h2>What Happens at the End of a CVL</h2>\n\n<p>Once all assets have been realised, distributions made, and investigations concluded, the liquidator files a final account with Companies House and sends notice to all creditors.</p>\n\n<p>Three months after that filing, the company is automatically dissolved. It ceases to exist as a legal entity. The company name becomes available for re-use (subject to restrictions under the Insolvency Act 1986 s.216, which prevents directors from re-using a company name or a similar name for five years without court permission).</p>\n\n<p>After dissolution, directors are free to start a new company, provided they have not been disqualified. Any personal guarantees given by directors survive the liquidation and remain enforceable by the creditor who holds them. A CVL does not discharge personal guarantees.</p>\n\n<h2>Director Risks and Investigations</h2>\n\n<p>A CVL triggers mandatory scrutiny of director conduct. Understanding the specific risks helps directors prepare and reduces unnecessary anxiety.</p>\n\n<h3>Wrongful trading</h3>\n\n<p>Under s.214 of the Insolvency Act 1986, directors can be held personally liable if they continued trading after the point at which they knew (or should have known) that the company could not avoid insolvent liquidation. The test is objective: what would a reasonably diligent person in the director's position have concluded?</p>\n\n<p>The practical defence is to show that once insolvency became apparent, the director took steps to minimise losses to creditors. Seeking professional advice early and acting on it is the clearest evidence of that.</p>\n\n<h3>Disqualification</h3>\n\n<p>The Company Directors Disqualification Act 1986 gives the Insolvency Service the power to seek a disqualification order (banning a director from holding office for 2 to 15 years) based on the liquidator's conduct report. Common grounds include allowing HMRC debts to accumulate while paying other creditors, failing to maintain adequate accounting records, and continuing to trade at creditors' expense.</p>\n\n<p>Insolvency Service data shows that the majority of CVLs do not result in disqualification proceedings, but the risk is real for directors who traded irresponsibly or failed to engage with the process.</p>\n\n<h3>Director liability agreements (DLAs)</h3>\n\n<p>In some cases, the liquidator may seek a contribution from directors through a formal claim or negotiated settlement, particularly where preferences (paying one creditor ahead of others in the run-up to liquidation) or transactions at undervalue have occurred. These claims are funded from the liquidation estate or through litigation funding.</p>\n\n<p>For a full breakdown of personal exposure during liquidation, see the <a href=\"/what-happens-to-a-director-during-liquidation/\">director risk guide</a>.</p>\n\n<h2>Alternatives to a CVL</h2>\n\n<p>A CVL is not the only option for an insolvent company. The right route depends on whether rescue is realistic, whether creditors are already forcing the issue, and the company's financial position.</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Compulsory liquidation:</strong> If a creditor (usually HMRC) files a winding-up petition and the company does not respond, the court can order compulsory winding up. Directors lose all control, the Official Receiver is appointed, and the process is more intrusive and less predictable than a CVL. See the <a href=\"/compulsory-liquidation/\">compulsory liquidation guide</a>.</li>\n\n  <li><strong>Company Voluntary Arrangement (CVA):</strong> If the business is viable but burdened by debt, a CVA allows the company to agree a repayment plan with creditors and continue trading. This requires 75% creditor approval and a realistic repayment proposal. It is a rescue tool, not a closure tool. See the <a href=\"/company-rescue-solutions/company-voluntary-arrangement/\">CVA guide</a>.</li>\n\n  <li><strong>Administration:</strong> Provides a statutory moratorium (protection from creditor action) while a rescue plan is developed. Suitable for larger businesses with ongoing revenue and realisable assets. More expensive and complex than a CVL. See the <a href=\"/insolvency/\">insolvency overview</a> for how administration fits into the wider framework.</li>\n\n  <li><strong>Strike-off (dissolution):</strong> Costs 10 pounds and is available for companies with no significant debts, no active creditor claims, and no assets to distribute. Not appropriate for insolvent companies because creditors can object and HMRC can restore the company to the register. See the <a href=\"/company-strike-off-and-dissolution/\">strike-off guide</a> for eligibility and risks.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>If the company is solvent and directors want a tax-efficient extraction of remaining funds, a <a href=\"/members-voluntary-liquidation/\">Members' Voluntary Liquidation (MVL)</a> is the relevant procedure, not a CVL.</p>\n\n<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>\n\n<details>\n  <summary>Can directors choose the insolvency practitioner in a CVL?</summary>\n  <p>Directors propose the IP, but creditors have the right to appoint a different one during the decision procedure. In practice, creditors rarely exercise this right in small-company CVLs, so the directors' choice usually stands.</p>\n</details>\n\n<details>\n  <summary>Do directors need to attend a creditors' meeting?</summary>\n  <p>Physical meetings are no longer mandatory. The Insolvency Rules 2016 replaced them with a \"decision procedure\" that can be conducted by correspondence (deemed consent). Creditors can request a meeting, but this is uncommon. Directors may need to answer questions from the liquidator or creditors in writing.</p>\n</details>\n\n<details>\n  <summary>What happens to employees in a CVL?</summary>\n  <p>Employees are made redundant when the liquidator is appointed (or when trading ceases, if earlier). They can claim statutory redundancy pay, unpaid wages (up to 8 weeks), holiday pay, and notice pay from the Redundancy Payments Service. These are preferential claims under the Insolvency Act 1986.</p>\n</details>\n\n<details>\n  <summary>Can HMRC block a CVL?</summary>\n  <p>HMRC cannot block a CVL. The decision to enter a CVL is made by the shareholders, not creditors. However, if HMRC has already filed a winding-up petition, the court process may overtake the CVL unless the petition is withdrawn or the CVL is commenced before the hearing date.</p>\n</details>\n\n<details>\n  <summary>Does a CVL affect the director's credit rating?</summary>\n  <p>A CVL does not directly appear on a director's personal credit file. However, any personal guarantees that are called in, or personal insolvency that follows (bankruptcy or an IVA), will affect the director's credit rating. Director disqualification is a public record held by the Insolvency Service.</p>\n</details>\n\n<details>\n  <summary>What if the company has no assets at all?</summary>\n  <p>A CVL can proceed even if the company has no realisable assets. The IP's fees must still be paid, typically upfront by the directors. This is one reason redundancy funding is relevant: it can provide the funds to cover liquidation costs.</p>\n</details>\n\n<details>\n  <summary>Can a CVL be reversed once started?</summary>\n  <p>Once the liquidator is appointed, the process is extremely difficult to reverse. The court can stay or terminate a winding up under s.112 of the Insolvency Act 1986, but this requires an application supported by evidence that the company is in fact solvent. In practice, reversal almost never happens.</p>\n</details>\n\n<details>\n  <summary>What happens to company bank accounts?</summary>\n  <p>The liquidator takes control of all company bank accounts on appointment. Any remaining balances become part of the liquidation estate. Directors cannot withdraw funds after the liquidator's appointment. Banks typically freeze accounts as soon as they are notified of the liquidation.</p>\n</details>\n\n<details>\n  <summary>Are bounce-back loans treated differently in a CVL?</summary>\n  <p>Bounce-back loans are unsecured debts and rank alongside other unsecured creditors. The government guarantee protects the lender, not the borrower. Directors are not personally liable for the loan unless they gave a personal guarantee or the loan was misused (which can trigger separate investigation). The liquidator will review how the loan funds were applied.</p>\n</details>\n\n<details>\n  <summary>How soon after a CVL can a director start a new company?</summary>\n  <p>Immediately, unless the director has been disqualified. The restriction under s.216 of the Insolvency Act 1986 applies to the company name (or a similar name), not to directorship itself. A disqualified director cannot act as a director of any company for the duration of the disqualification (2 to 15 years).</p>\n</details>\n\n<h2>What to Do Now</h2>\n\n<p>The right next step depends on how immediate the pressure is.</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>If the company is still trading but clearly insolvent:</strong> speak to a licensed insolvency practitioner this week. Early engagement protects against wrongful trading risk and preserves the option of a controlled CVL rather than forced compulsory liquidation.</li>\n\n  <li><strong>If a winding-up petition has been filed or a statutory demand received:</strong> act within days, not weeks. A CVL can still be started, but only if the petition hearing has not yet taken place. Delay past this point removes the voluntary option entirely.</li>\n\n  <li><strong>If trading has already stopped and debts remain:</strong> the company still needs a formal closure route. Leaving it dormant with unpaid creditors does not remove the liabilities or the risk of compulsory action. A CVL resolves the position definitively.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Company Debt works with licensed insolvency practitioners who handle CVLs for owner-managed businesses across the UK. Initial consultations are free and confidential. If redundancy funding applies, the team will confirm eligibility before any commitment.</p>\n\n<p>Call <strong>0800 074 6757</strong> or use the contact form to arrange a same-day consultation.</p>","7680":"<h2>If your company is facing a winding-up petition, you still have options</h2>\n\n<p>Receiving a winding-up petition is one of the most urgent situations a director can face. Your bank account may be frozen within days. A notice will appear in <a href=\"https://www.thegazette.co.uk/\">The Gazette</a>, visible to customers, suppliers, and lenders. If the court grants the order, the Official Receiver takes control of the company and your authority as director ends.</p>\n\n<p>That is the trajectory if nothing is done. But a petition does not automatically mean the company is finished. Directors who act within the legal window still have routes available: paying or settling the debt, challenging the petition on valid grounds, or moving to a voluntary process that preserves more control.</p>\n\n<p>This page covers what compulsory liquidation means, what happens at each stage, what you risk by waiting, and what you can do right now to protect your position.</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>If you have received a statutory demand:</strong> you typically have 21 days before a petition can be issued. Use that time to get advice. Call a licensed insolvency practitioner today.</li>\n  <li><strong>If a petition has already been filed:</strong> the hearing is usually 8 to 10 weeks away, but your bank may freeze the account as soon as it sees the Gazette notice. Act the same day.</li>\n  <li><strong>If a winding-up order has been made:</strong> the Official Receiver is now in control. Your options are limited, but you still have rights. <a href=\"/what-happens-to-a-director-during-liquidation/\">Read what this means for directors</a>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Company Debt offers free, confidential advice from licensed insolvency practitioners, available 24 hours a day, 7 days a week. If you are facing a petition, speak to the team now on <strong>0800 074 6757</strong>.</p>\n\n\n<h2>What compulsory liquidation means</h2>\n\n<p>Compulsory liquidation is the forced closure of a company by court order. It is not something a director chooses. It happens because a creditor, most commonly HMRC, has asked the court to wind the company up.</p>\n\n<p>Once a winding-up order is granted, the Official Receiver (a government-appointed officer) takes control of the company. Directors lose the power to manage the business, access company bank accounts, or dispose of company assets. The company stops trading and its assets are collected, sold, and distributed to creditors.</p>\n\n<p>The legal basis sits in the <a href=\"/insolvency/\">Insolvency Act 1986</a>. The court can order compulsory liquidation if it is satisfied the company cannot pay its debts, under section 122(1)(f).</p>\n\n<p>The distinction that matters: in a <a href=\"/creditors-voluntary-liquidation-cvl/\">creditors' voluntary liquidation (CVL)</a>, directors initiate the process and choose the insolvency practitioner. In compulsory liquidation, the creditor forces it and the Official Receiver is appointed. That difference affects cost, speed, director scrutiny, and whether employees can claim statutory redundancy pay through the normal route.</p>\n\n\n<h2>Why this matters right now</h2>\n\n<p>Compulsory liquidation is not a background legal process. It triggers immediate, practical consequences that affect the director personally and the company operationally.</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Bank account freeze.</strong> Banks routinely freeze company accounts when they become aware of a winding-up petition, often after the Gazette notice is published. This can happen before the court hearing, cutting off cash flow, payroll, and supplier payments overnight.</li>\n  <li><strong>Gazette publication.</strong> The petition is advertised in The London Gazette at least 7 business days before the hearing. This is a public record. Customers, suppliers, landlords, and lenders can see it.</li>\n  <li><strong>Loss of director control.</strong> Once the winding-up order is made, the directors have no authority to act on behalf of the company. The Official Receiver manages everything from that point.</li>\n  <li><strong>Director investigation.</strong> The Official Receiver is required to investigate the conduct of directors. If wrongful or fraudulent trading is found, directors can face personal liability, disqualification for up to 15 years, or both.</li>\n  <li><strong>Employee impact.</strong> Employees are automatically dismissed when a winding-up order is made. Redundancy claims go through the Redundancy Payments Service rather than the employer.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>The practical issue is timing. Once the petition is advertised, the damage to the company's reputation and banking relationships has already started, regardless of the court outcome.</p>\n\n\n<h2>What happens if the petition is ignored</h2>\n\n<p>Doing nothing is the most damaging option. If a winding-up petition is served and no response is filed, the court will almost certainly grant the winding-up order.</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>No defence filed:</strong> the court treats the debt as undisputed. The order is made on paper or at a short hearing. There is no second chance.</li>\n  <li><strong>Bank account frozen before hearing:</strong> most UK banks freeze accounts on sight of the Gazette notice. Directors often find this out when payroll fails or a supplier payment bounces.</li>\n  <li><strong>Official Receiver appointed:</strong> the company is placed into compulsory liquidation immediately. Directors must cooperate with the OR's investigation, hand over all company records, and attend interviews if required.</li>\n  <li><strong>Director conduct scrutiny intensifies:</strong> ignoring a petition does not look like an oversight. The OR and the Insolvency Service will look closely at whether directors continued trading while knowing the company was insolvent.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>The window to respond is short. Between service of the petition and the hearing, directors have 8 to 10 weeks in most cases. But the real pressure point is the Gazette advertisement, which triggers the bank freeze. That happens much sooner.</p>\n\n\n<h2>Immediate steps to take</h2>\n\n<p>If you have received a winding-up petition or a statutory demand, these are the actions available to you. The right step depends on whether the debt is disputed, whether the company can pay, and how much time remains.</p>\n\n<ol>\n  <li><strong>Check the deadline.</strong> A statutory demand gives 21 days. A winding-up petition hearing is typically 8 to 10 weeks from issue. Both deadlines are hard.</li>\n  <li><strong>Decide whether the debt is genuinely disputed.</strong> If you have a legitimate reason to challenge the debt (the amount is wrong, the goods were defective, the invoice was already paid), you may be able to apply to have the petition dismissed or restrained. The court can do this if the debt is disputed on substantial grounds.</li>\n  <li><strong>Pay the debt in full.</strong> If the company can pay the petitioning creditor, paying the full amount owed (including legal costs) before the hearing will usually result in the petition being dismissed.</li>\n  <li><strong>Negotiate a settlement.</strong> Creditors sometimes agree to withdraw the petition if a payment plan or partial settlement is offered. This needs to happen quickly and in writing.</li>\n  <li><strong>Consider a voluntary route.</strong> If the company cannot pay its debts but wants to close on its own terms, a <a href=\"/creditors-voluntary-liquidation-cvl/\">creditors' voluntary liquidation (CVL)</a> may be available. This allows directors to choose the insolvency practitioner and typically results in less scrutiny than compulsory liquidation.</li>\n  <li><strong>Get licensed advice immediately.</strong> A licensed insolvency practitioner can assess the position, identify which options are still open, and act on the same day if needed.</li>\n</ol>\n\n<p>Delaying past the Gazette notice point makes every option harder. The bank freeze alone can make it impossible to fund a settlement or pay for a voluntary process.</p>\n\n\n<h2>Legal grounds: who can petition and on what basis</h2>\n\n<p>Compulsory liquidation is governed by the Insolvency Act 1986. The key sections are:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Section 122(1)(f):</strong> the court may order winding up if the company is unable to pay its debts.</li>\n  <li><strong>Section 123:</strong> defines what \"unable to pay its debts\" means. The two main tests are the cash-flow test (the company cannot pay debts as they fall due) and the balance-sheet test (liabilities exceed assets).</li>\n  <li><strong>Section 124:</strong> sets out who can present a winding-up petition. This includes creditors, the company itself, directors, shareholders, the Secretary of State, and certain regulatory bodies.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>In practice, HMRC is the petitioner in the majority of compulsory liquidation cases. HMRC petitions have risen sharply since the end of the COVID-era enforcement pause, and HMRC now accounts for around 60% of all winding-up petitions. [HUMAN CONFIRMATION NEEDED: verify current HMRC petition share percentage]</p>\n\n<p>The minimum debt threshold for a winding-up petition is <strong>£750</strong>, set by s.123(1)(a) of the Insolvency Act 1986. In practice, most petitions involve debts of several thousand pounds or more, but the legal threshold is low.</p>\n\n<p>A creditor does not need to prove the company is balance-sheet insolvent. Failure to pay a debt of £750 or more within 21 days of a statutory demand is enough to establish a presumption of inability to pay under the Act.</p>\n\n\n<h2>The court process</h2>\n\n<p>The winding-up process follows a fixed legal sequence. Knowing the stages helps directors identify where they still have options.</p>\n\n<ol>\n  <li><strong>Statutory demand served.</strong> The creditor sends a formal demand for payment. The company has 21 days to pay. If the debt is not paid or disputed, the creditor can issue a petition.</li>\n  <li><strong>Winding-up petition filed.</strong> The petition is filed at court. The petitioner must serve it on the company at its registered office.</li>\n  <li><strong>Gazette advertisement.</strong> The petition must be advertised in The London Gazette at least 7 business days before the hearing. This is the trigger point for bank freezes and reputational damage.</li>\n  <li><strong>Court hearing.</strong> The court hears the petition, typically 8 to 10 weeks after issue. Possible outcomes:\n    <ul>\n      <li>Winding-up order made (company is placed into compulsory liquidation)</li>\n      <li>Petition dismissed (debt paid or legitimately disputed)</li>\n      <li>Petition adjourned (more time given, often for payment negotiations)</li>\n      <li>Petition stayed (if a voluntary arrangement is proposed)</li>\n    </ul>\n  </li>\n  <li><strong>Official Receiver appointed.</strong> If the order is made, the Official Receiver becomes liquidator. A private insolvency practitioner may later be appointed if creditors request it.</li>\n  <li><strong>Investigation and asset realisation.</strong> The OR investigates director conduct, collects company assets, and distributes proceeds to creditors in the statutory order of priority.</li>\n</ol>\n\n<p>The entire process from petition to final dissolution can take 12 months or longer. For directors, the critical period is the weeks between the petition being filed and the hearing date.</p>\n\n\n<h2>What directors should avoid doing</h2>\n\n<p>Once a company is facing a <a href=\"/winding-up-petitions/\">winding-up petition</a>, certain actions by directors will make the situation significantly worse. Some carry personal liability. Others are criminal offences.</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Do not pay one creditor ahead of others to reduce pressure.</strong> Paying a connected creditor (a director's loan account, a family member's invoice, a related company) when the company is insolvent is a preference under s.239 of the Insolvency Act 1986. The liquidator can reverse the payment and pursue the director personally.</li>\n  <li><strong>Do not move or sell company assets below value.</strong> Transactions at an undervalue (s.238 IA 1986) can be reversed. Transferring stock, vehicles, equipment, or property to connected parties while the company is insolvent will be investigated.</li>\n  <li><strong>Do not continue trading if there is no reasonable prospect of paying creditors.</strong> Wrongful trading under s.214 IA 1986 can result in the director being ordered to contribute personally to the company's debts. The test is whether a reasonably diligent person would have concluded there was no reasonable prospect of avoiding insolvent liquidation.</li>\n  <li><strong>Do not ignore the Official Receiver.</strong> Directors are legally required to cooperate with the OR, provide company records, attend interviews, and complete a questionnaire. Non-cooperation can lead to arrest, contempt of court, and a longer disqualification period.</li>\n  <li><strong>Do not destroy company records.</strong> Destroying or concealing company books and records is a criminal offence under s.209 and s.210 IA 1986.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>The theme is straightforward: actions that protect the director at the expense of creditors will be scrutinised and, where found, penalised.</p>\n\n\n<h2>What this means for directors, employees, and bank accounts</h2>\n\n<h3>For directors</h3>\n\n<p>Directors are automatically removed from their management role when the winding-up order is made. They must cooperate with the Official Receiver's investigation into the company's affairs and their own conduct as directors.</p>\n\n<p>If the investigation reveals wrongful trading, fraudulent trading, or misfeasance, directors may face:</p>\n<ul>\n  <li>Personal liability for company debts (wrongful trading claims under s.214)</li>\n  <li>Disqualification from acting as a director for between 2 and 15 years</li>\n  <li>Criminal prosecution in cases of fraud or deliberate concealment</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Personal guarantees (commonly given for commercial leases, bank lending, or HMRC time-to-pay arrangements) survive liquidation. If a director has personally guaranteed a debt, the creditor can pursue the director directly after the company enters liquidation. <a href=\"/what-happens-to-a-director-during-liquidation/\">Read more about director exposure during liquidation</a>.</p>\n\n<h3>For employees</h3>\n\n<p>Employees are automatically dismissed on the date of the winding-up order. They become preferential creditors for certain claims (up to 4 months' unpaid wages, capped at £800 per employee, plus accrued holiday pay).</p>\n\n<p>Redundancy pay, notice pay, and unpaid wages beyond the preferential cap are claimed through the government's Redundancy Payments Service (part of the Insolvency Service), not from the company directly. This process typically takes 3 to 6 weeks after the claim is submitted.</p>\n\n<h3>For bank accounts</h3>\n\n<p>Company bank accounts are frozen either when the bank becomes aware of the petition (usually via the Gazette notice) or when the winding-up order is made. Any disposition of company property after the petition is presented is void unless the court orders otherwise (s.127 IA 1986).</p>\n\n<p>This means payments made from the company account after the petition date, including wages, supplier payments, and rent, may need to be returned to the liquidator. Directors should seek a validation order from the court if they need to continue making essential payments before the hearing.</p>\n\n\n<h2>When professional advice becomes urgent</h2>\n\n<p>The urgency depends on where you are in the process. Both stages below require same-day or next-day action.</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Statutory demand received:</strong> the 21-day clock is running. If the debt is disputed, the company may be able to apply to set the demand aside. If the debt is owed, the company needs to pay it or negotiate before the creditor petitions. A licensed insolvency practitioner can assess the position and advise on options the same day.</li>\n  <li><strong>Winding-up petition served:</strong> this is a legal emergency. Once the petition is advertised in the Gazette, bank accounts can freeze. Directors need advice before the advertisement, not after. Same-day contact with a licensed IP is not an overreaction at this stage.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Waiting to \"see what happens\" is the most common mistake. By the time the bank account is frozen, the company's ability to fund a settlement, a CVL, or any alternative is severely compromised.</p>\n\n<p>The <a href=\"/insolvency-test/\">insolvency test</a> can help you understand whether the company meets the legal definition of insolvency. But if a petition is already in play, the test is secondary to getting advice on the petition itself.</p>\n\n<p>Company Debt provides free, confidential advice from licensed insolvency practitioners. The team is available 24/7, including evenings and weekends. Call <strong>0800 074 6757</strong>.</p>\n\n\n<h2>Alternatives that may still be available</h2>\n\n<p>Even after a winding-up petition has been filed, some alternatives may remain open. Which ones depend on the company's financial position, how much time is left before the hearing, and whether the petitioning creditor will agree.</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Pay the debt.</strong> If the company or a third party can pay the full petitioning debt plus the creditor's legal costs, the petition will usually be dismissed. This is the most direct route but requires available cash.</li>\n  <li><strong>Creditors' Voluntary Liquidation (CVL).</strong> If the company is insolvent and closure is inevitable, directors can initiate a <a href=\"/creditors-voluntary-liquidation-cvl/\">CVL</a> before the winding-up order is made. A CVL allows directors to choose the insolvency practitioner, typically involves less scrutiny than compulsory liquidation, and may preserve employee access to statutory redundancy pay through the normal route.</li>\n  <li><strong>Company Voluntary Arrangement (CVA).</strong> A CVA is a formal agreement to repay creditors over time, supervised by an insolvency practitioner. It requires 75% creditor approval by value. If accepted, the petition is usually stayed. This route suits companies that are viable but temporarily unable to pay. It is not available if the company has no future income to fund the arrangement.</li>\n  <li><strong>Administration.</strong> If the company has a viable business that could be rescued or sold as a going concern, administration may be appropriate. An administrator is appointed to manage the company and can block further action by creditors, including winding-up petitions. This route requires a realistic rescue plan and is usually more expensive than a CVL.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>The window for these alternatives narrows as the process advances. Before the Gazette notice, most options are still available. After the bank freeze, funding any of them becomes the primary obstacle.</p>\n\n<p>Not every company in this position qualifies for every route. A licensed IP can assess which alternatives are realistic based on the company's actual financial position, not which ones sound appealing in theory.</p>\n\n\n<h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>\n\n<details>\n  <summary>Can a winding-up petition be stopped?</summary>\n  <p>Yes, in several ways. The debt can be paid in full (including the petitioner's costs), the petition can be dismissed if the debt is genuinely disputed on substantial grounds, or the court can adjourn or stay the petition if a voluntary arrangement or other proposal is made. The earlier you act, the more options remain. Once the winding-up order is made, it can only be rescinded in limited circumstances.</p>\n</details>\n\n<details>\n  <summary>How quickly does the bank account freeze?</summary>\n  <p>Most UK banks freeze company accounts as soon as they become aware of a winding-up petition, typically when the Gazette notice is published. This can happen 7 or more business days before the court hearing. Some banks act even earlier if they receive the petition directly. The freeze happens without warning and applies to all funds in the account.</p>\n</details>\n\n<details>\n  <summary>Will I lose my house?</summary>\n  <p>Compulsory liquidation of a limited company does not automatically affect personal assets, including your home. However, if you have given a personal guarantee for any company debt (common with bank loans, commercial leases, and some HMRC time-to-pay arrangements), the creditor can pursue you personally. If you cannot pay a personally guaranteed debt, your home could be at risk. This is a question for early legal advice, not something to guess about.</p>\n</details>\n\n<details>\n  <summary>Is compulsory liquidation the same as bankruptcy?</summary>\n  <p>No. Compulsory liquidation applies to companies. Bankruptcy applies to individuals. A director whose company is wound up is not personally bankrupt unless they separately fail to pay personal debts (including any triggered by personal guarantees). The two processes are legally distinct, though one can follow the other in some circumstances.</p>\n</details>\n\n<details>\n  <summary>What happens to employees?</summary>\n  <p>Employees are automatically dismissed on the date the winding-up order is made. They can claim redundancy pay, unpaid wages (up to 8 weeks, capped at the statutory weekly limit), notice pay, and accrued holiday pay through the government's Redundancy Payments Service. Claims are typically processed within 3 to 6 weeks. Employees do not need the employer's cooperation to make a claim.</p>\n</details>\n\n<details>\n  <summary>Can I still be a director of another company?</summary>\n  <p>Being a director of a company that goes into compulsory liquidation does not automatically disqualify you. However, the Official Receiver will investigate your conduct. If the investigation finds unfit conduct (wrongful trading, preferences, breach of duty), the Insolvency Service can apply for a disqualification order, banning you from acting as a director for between 2 and 15 years. Until any investigation is concluded, you are not prevented from holding other directorships, but you should take advice on the risk.</p>\n</details>\n\n<details>\n  <summary>What does the Official Receiver do?</summary>\n  <p>The Official Receiver is a civil servant employed by the Insolvency Service. After a winding-up order, the OR takes control of the company, investigates the conduct of directors, collects and realises company assets, adjudicates creditor claims, and distributes proceeds in the statutory order of priority. The OR may also report to the Secretary of State on whether directors should be disqualified. Directors are legally required to cooperate fully with the OR.</p>\n</details>\n\n<details>\n  <summary>How much does compulsory liquidation cost?</summary>\n  <p>The petitioning creditor pays the court fee (currently £2,167, which includes a £1,600 deposit to the Official Receiver and a £567 court fee). [HUMAN CONFIRMATION NEEDED: verify current compulsory liquidation court fee and OR deposit amounts] The director does not pay these costs directly, but the company's assets are used to cover the OR's costs and expenses before any distribution to creditors. If the company has no assets, the OR's costs are met from the deposit.</p>\n</details>\n\n<details>\n  <summary>Can I convert a compulsory liquidation to a CVL?</summary>\n  <p>Once a winding-up order has been made, it is not possible to convert to a CVL. The CVL route is only available before the order is granted. This is one of the main reasons directors are advised to act quickly after receiving a petition: if voluntary liquidation is a better outcome, it must be initiated before the court hearing, not after.</p>\n</details>\n\n<details>\n  <summary>What happens to company debts after compulsory liquidation?</summary>\n  <p>Company debts are dealt with through the liquidation process. The liquidator distributes available assets to creditors in the statutory priority order: secured creditors, preferential creditors (employees for certain claims), unsecured creditors with a prescribed part allocation, then remaining unsecured creditors. Any debts not covered by available assets are written off when the company is dissolved. Personal guarantees, however, are not extinguished by company liquidation and remain enforceable against the director personally.</p>\n</details>\n\n\n<h2>Urgent next steps</h2>\n\n<p>The right action depends on where you are now.</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>You have received a statutory demand and the 21 days have not expired:</strong> get advice today. A licensed insolvency practitioner can assess whether the debt is disputable, whether the company can pay, and what to do before the deadline. This is the point with the most options.</li>\n  <li><strong>A winding-up petition has been filed but not yet advertised in the Gazette:</strong> act the same day. This is the last window before the bank freeze risk becomes real. Options include paying the debt, applying for an adjournment, or initiating a CVL.</li>\n  <li><strong>The petition has been advertised and/or the bank account is frozen:</strong> contact an insolvency practitioner immediately. Funding options are reduced but not necessarily zero. The hearing date sets the hard deadline.</li>\n  <li><strong>A winding-up order has been made:</strong> cooperate with the Official Receiver. Your obligations are now legal, not optional. Take personal advice on any personal guarantees or director liability concerns.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Company Debt's licensed insolvency practitioners provide free, confidential advice 24 hours a day, 7 days a week. No obligation, no judgement, and no cost for the initial call.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Call now: 0800 074 6757</strong></p>\n\n<p>Or <a href=\"/insolvency/\">visit the insolvency hub</a> to read more about <a href=\"/liquidation/\">liquidation options</a>, <a href=\"/creditors-voluntary-liquidation-cvl/\">creditors' voluntary liquidation</a>, or <a href=\"/winding-up-petitions/\">winding-up petitions</a>.</p>","7687":"<h2>A creditor is trying to force your company into liquidation. You have days, not weeks, to respond.</h2>\n\n<p>If a winding-up petition has been filed against your company, your bank account is likely to be frozen within hours of the petition appearing in the London Gazette. Once that happens, trading becomes almost impossible. The court will not wait for you to catch up.</p>\n\n<p>This is not a warning letter you can set aside. A winding-up petition is a formal application to the High Court asking a judge to order the compulsory liquidation of your company. If you do not respond before the hearing date, the court can grant a winding-up order in your absence. At that point, control passes to the Official Receiver and you lose the ability to influence what happens next.</p>\n\n<p>The window to act is short. Most petitions allow 7 to 14 days before the hearing. Some directors have less. If you have received a petition, or a statutory demand that could lead to one, the priority is to understand your options and act before the court date.</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Bank freeze risk:</strong> Most UK banks freeze company accounts as soon as the petition appears in the Gazette</li>\n  <li><strong>Hearing window:</strong> Typically 7 to 14 days from service to court date</li>\n  <li><strong>Automatic outcome if ignored:</strong> Winding-up order and appointment of the Official Receiver</li>\n  <li><strong>Your options narrow fast:</strong> Every day of delay removes a possible defence or negotiation route</li>\n</ul>\n\n\n<h2>What a Winding-Up Petition Actually Is</h2>\n\n<p>A winding-up petition is a legal application made to the court by a creditor (or sometimes HMRC) asking for your company to be compulsorily wound up. It is governed by the Insolvency Act 1986 and typically follows an unpaid statutory demand or an undisputed debt of £750 or more.</p>\n\n<p>The petition is not a negotiation tool. It is the final step in a formal escalation process. Once filed, it becomes a matter of public record when it is advertised in the London Gazette, and that Gazette notice is what triggers the bank freeze.</p>\n\n<p>The creditor must serve the petition on the company (usually at its registered office) and then advertise it in the Gazette at least 7 business days before the hearing. The company then has until the hearing date to respond.</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Who can file:</strong> Any creditor owed £750 or more (including HMRC), or the company itself</li>\n  <li><strong>Legal basis:</strong> Sections 122-124 of the Insolvency Act 1986</li>\n  <li><strong>Court:</strong> Usually the High Court (Companies Court) in London, or a District Registry</li>\n  <li><strong>Cost to the creditor:</strong> Court fee of £302 plus a £1,600 petition deposit</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>HMRC is the most frequent petitioner. If your petition comes from HMRC, the dynamics are different. HMRC petitions often follow a specific escalation sequence and may have additional complications. See our guide to <a href=\"/winding-up-petitions/dealing-with-an-hmrc-winding-up-petition/\">dealing with an HMRC winding-up petition</a> for the detail on that route.</p>\n\n\n<h2>Why This Matters Right Now</h2>\n\n<p>The damage from a winding-up petition does not start at the court hearing. It starts the moment the petition is advertised in the London Gazette.</p>\n\n<p>Here is the typical sequence once a petition is filed:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Day 1 (petition served):</strong> The company receives formal notice. The hearing date is set, usually 7 to 14 days away.</li>\n  <li><strong>Day 7+ (Gazette publication):</strong> The petition is advertised in the London Gazette. Banks run automated checks against the Gazette. Most major UK banks freeze the company account within 24 hours of publication.</li>\n  <li><strong>Bank freeze:</strong> Once the account is frozen, you cannot pay wages, suppliers, rent, or HMRC. Trading effectively stops.</li>\n  <li><strong>Creditor pile-on:</strong> Other creditors see the Gazette notice and may file supporting petitions or accelerate their own recovery action.</li>\n  <li><strong>Court hearing:</strong> If you have not resolved the petition by the hearing date, the judge can make a winding-up order.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>The bank freeze is the immediate crisis. Directors often assume they have until the hearing to act. In practice, the Gazette publication can make the company unviable days before the court even sits.</p>\n\n<p>If your company relies on its bank account to operate (which nearly all do), the Gazette advertisement is the real deadline, not the hearing.</p>\n\n\n<h2>What Happens If the Petition Is Ignored</h2>\n\n<p>If you do nothing, the court will almost certainly grant a winding-up order at the hearing. The consequences are immediate and severe:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Official Receiver appointed:</strong> The Official Receiver (a government officer) takes control of the company. You lose all authority as a director.</li>\n  <li><strong>Assets seized:</strong> Company assets are collected and sold to pay creditors. You have no say in how they are valued or sold.</li>\n  <li><strong>Director investigation:</strong> The Official Receiver is legally required to investigate the conduct of every director. This includes examining whether debts were incurred when the company had no reasonable prospect of repaying them.</li>\n  <li><strong>Wrongful trading risk:</strong> If the investigation finds that you continued trading when you knew (or should have known) the company was insolvent, you can be held personally liable for the company's debts from that point onwards.</li>\n  <li><strong>Disqualification risk:</strong> Serious misconduct findings can lead to director disqualification for up to 15 years.</li>\n  <li><strong>Public record:</strong> The compulsory liquidation is permanently recorded at Companies House.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>A compulsory liquidation through the court is the worst outcome for directors. It removes your control, maximises your personal exposure, and creates the longest paper trail. See our full guide to <a href=\"/compulsory-liquidation/\">compulsory liquidation</a> for what the process involves.</p>\n\n\n<h2>Immediate Steps You Can Take</h2>\n\n<p>You have several options once a petition has been filed. The right one depends on whether the debt is genuinely owed, whether the company can pay, and whether the company is still viable.</p>\n\n<h3>1. Pay the debt in full (plus costs)</h3>\n\n<p>If the company can pay the full amount claimed plus the petitioner's legal costs, paying before the hearing will usually result in the petition being withdrawn or dismissed. This is the cleanest resolution, but only works if the funds are available and the debt is not disputed.</p>\n\n<h3>2. Dispute the debt</h3>\n\n<p>If the debt is genuinely disputed on substantial grounds, you can apply to have the petition struck out or restrained by injunction. The court will not wind up a company over a debt that is legitimately contested. But the dispute must be real. Tactical objections raised for the first time after the petition is filed are unlikely to succeed.</p>\n\n<h3>3. Negotiate a payment arrangement</h3>\n\n<p>If the company cannot pay immediately but has the means to pay over time, it may be possible to negotiate a payment plan with the petitioning creditor. If the creditor agrees, they can apply to have the petition adjourned or withdrawn. Time pressure works against you here.</p>\n\n<h3>4. Apply for a validation order</h3>\n\n<p>Once a petition is filed, any payments from the company's bank account after that date can be voided by the court under Section 127 of the Insolvency Act. A validation order from the court authorises specific payments (wages, essential suppliers, HMRC) to continue despite the petition. This is critical if the bank has not yet frozen the account or if you need to keep the business running while you resolve the situation.</p>\n\n<h3>5. Move to a Creditors' Voluntary Liquidation (CVL)</h3>\n\n<p>If the company is insolvent and cannot realistically trade its way out, converting to a <a href=\"/creditors-voluntary-liquidation-cvl/\">Creditors' Voluntary Liquidation (CVL)</a> may be the best remaining option. A CVL is a director-led liquidation. You appoint a licensed insolvency practitioner of your choosing, the process is more orderly, and the director investigation is typically less aggressive than in a compulsory winding-up. It also gives directors more influence over how assets are realised and how creditors are dealt with.</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Debt is owed and company can pay →</strong> pay in full plus costs</li>\n  <li><strong>Debt is genuinely disputed →</strong> apply to strike out or restrain the petition</li>\n  <li><strong>Debt is owed but company needs time →</strong> negotiate adjournment</li>\n  <li><strong>Company is insolvent but still operating →</strong> apply for validation order while arranging CVL</li>\n  <li><strong>Company cannot continue →</strong> move to CVL before the hearing</li>\n</ul>\n\n\n<h2>Statutory Demands and Petitions: The Escalation Path</h2>\n\n<p>Most winding-up petitions do not arrive without warning. The typical escalation runs like this:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Unpaid debt:</strong> The creditor chases payment through letters, calls, or debt collection agents.</li>\n  <li><strong>Statutory demand:</strong> A formal written demand for payment, giving the company 21 days to pay or reach an agreement. This is the formal precursor to a petition.</li>\n  <li><strong>Winding-up petition:</strong> If the statutory demand is not satisfied within 21 days, the creditor can file a petition with the court.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>The statutory demand is the critical intervention point. If you have received a statutory demand but no petition has been filed yet, you have more options and more time. The 21-day window from a statutory demand is when negotiation, dispute, or restructuring is most effective.</p>\n\n<p>Once the petition is filed, the dynamics change. The Gazette publication triggers the bank freeze, other creditors may pile on, and the court hearing imposes a hard deadline.</p>\n\n<p>If you are at the statutory demand stage, act this week. If a petition has already been filed, act today. Use our <a href=\"/insolvency-test/\">insolvency test</a> to assess whether the company can pay its debts as they fall due.</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Statutory demand received:</strong> 21 days to respond. Negotiate, dispute, or pay.</li>\n  <li><strong>21 days expired, no petition yet:</strong> The creditor can file at any time. Do not assume they will not.</li>\n  <li><strong>Petition filed:</strong> 7 to 14 days to the hearing. Bank freeze likely within days of Gazette notice.</li>\n</ul>\n\n\n<h2>The Court Hearing</h2>\n\n<p>If the petition reaches the hearing without being resolved, a judge will decide the outcome. The hearing takes place at the Companies Court (part of the High Court) or at the relevant District Registry.</p>\n\n<p>The possible outcomes are:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Winding-up order:</strong> The court orders compulsory liquidation. The Official Receiver is appointed. The company ceases to exist as a going concern.</li>\n  <li><strong>Dismissal:</strong> The court dismisses the petition. This usually happens if the debt is genuinely disputed on substantial grounds or if the petitioning creditor has acted improperly.</li>\n  <li><strong>Adjournment:</strong> The court postpones the hearing, usually to allow the company time to pay or to complete a negotiation. Adjournments are not automatic. The judge needs a reason to believe the delay will lead to resolution.</li>\n  <li><strong>Stay of proceedings:</strong> The court pauses the petition, often where the company is pursuing a formal rescue route such as a Company Voluntary Arrangement or administration.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>If you want the court to dismiss, adjourn, or stay the petition, you need to appear at the hearing (or have legal representation appear) and present evidence. Simply filing a defence at the last minute is rarely enough. The court expects you to have engaged with the petitioner and to have a credible proposal.</p>\n\n<p>Directors who do not attend the hearing almost always receive a winding-up order.</p>\n\n\n<h2>What Directors Should Avoid Doing</h2>\n\n<p>Once a petition has been filed, certain actions can make your situation significantly worse:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Paying some creditors but not others:</strong> Preferential payments made after the company is insolvent can be clawed back by a liquidator and may result in personal liability for the director who authorised them.</li>\n  <li><strong>Moving or hiding company assets:</strong> Transferring assets to connected parties or hiding them from creditors is a criminal offence under the Insolvency Act. It will be discovered during the investigation.</li>\n  <li><strong>Continuing to trade on credit:</strong> Incurring new debts when you know the company cannot pay them is the definition of wrongful trading. It creates personal liability.</li>\n  <li><strong>Ignoring the petition and hoping it goes away:</strong> It will not. The court process continues whether or not you engage.</li>\n  <li><strong>Taking legal advice from online forums:</strong> Insolvency law is technical and situation-specific. Generic advice from business forums is often wrong and can lead to actions that worsen your legal position.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>The single most damaging thing a director can do is delay. Every day between receiving the petition and taking professional advice is a day where the situation deteriorates and your options narrow.</p>\n\n\n<h2>What This Means for Bank Accounts, Employees, and Directors</h2>\n\n<h3>Bank accounts</h3>\n\n<p>Most UK banks monitor the London Gazette for winding-up petitions. When your company's name appears, the bank will typically freeze the account within 24 hours. This means no payments in or out. Wages, direct debits, supplier payments, and HMRC payments all stop. A validation order (see above) can authorise specific essential payments, but you need to apply to the court before the freeze takes effect.</p>\n\n<h3>Employees</h3>\n\n<p>If the company enters compulsory liquidation, employees are automatically dismissed. They become preferential creditors for unpaid wages (up to £800), holiday pay, and notice pay. Redundancy payments are handled through the Redundancy Payments Service (part of the Insolvency Service), not from company funds. In a CVL, the process is more controlled. If directors move to a CVL before the court hearing, employees may be eligible for statutory redundancy pay funded through the National Insurance Fund.</p>\n\n<h3>Directors</h3>\n\n<p>A compulsory winding-up triggers a mandatory investigation into director conduct by the Official Receiver. This covers the period leading up to insolvency. The investigation examines whether directors traded while insolvent, took excessive remuneration, failed to keep proper records, or acted in their own interest rather than in the interest of creditors. Personal liability and disqualification are both possible outcomes. In a director-led CVL, the investigation is handled by the appointed insolvency practitioner and is typically less confrontational.</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Compulsory liquidation:</strong> Mandatory Official Receiver investigation, higher personal exposure, no choice of practitioner</li>\n  <li><strong>CVL (voluntary):</strong> Director chooses the insolvency practitioner, more orderly process, typically less aggressive investigation</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>The difference in outcome between compulsory and voluntary liquidation for directors is significant. Understanding this is the core reason to act before the petition hearing. See our guide to <a href=\"/liquidation/\">liquidation</a> for a full comparison of the routes.</p>\n\n\n<h2>When to Get Professional Help</h2>\n\n<p>The timing question is straightforward:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>If you have received a statutory demand:</strong> Speak to a licensed insolvency practitioner this week. You have up to 21 days, but the best outcomes happen when you engage early in that window.</li>\n  <li><strong>If a winding-up petition has been filed:</strong> Speak to a licensed insolvency practitioner today. Not tomorrow. The bank freeze, the hearing date, and the Gazette advertisement create a countdown that does not pause.</li>\n  <li><strong>If the petition is from HMRC:</strong> The same urgency applies, but HMRC petitions follow a specific pattern. See our <a href=\"/winding-up-petitions/dealing-with-an-hmrc-winding-up-petition/\">HMRC winding-up petition guide</a> for the detail.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>A licensed insolvency practitioner can assess whether the company can be saved, whether the petition can be challenged, and whether a CVL is the right route. They can also apply for a validation order if the bank account is at risk, and represent the company at the court hearing if needed.</p>\n\n<p>Free initial advice is standard across the insolvency profession. You do not need to pay upfront to understand your options.</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>What a licensed IP can do immediately:</strong> Assess viability, challenge the petition grounds, apply for validation orders, negotiate with the petitioning creditor, arrange a CVL if appropriate</li>\n  <li><strong>What they cannot do:</strong> Reverse a winding-up order once granted, unfreeze a bank account without a court order, guarantee a specific outcome at the hearing</li>\n</ul>\n\n\n<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>\n\n<details>\n  <summary>Can a winding-up petition be stopped after it has been filed?</summary>\n  <p>Yes. A petition can be stopped by paying the debt in full (plus the petitioner's costs), by successfully disputing the debt on substantial grounds, or by the petitioning creditor agreeing to withdraw it following a negotiation. The company can also ask the court to dismiss or adjourn the petition at the hearing. However, once a winding-up order has been granted, it is extremely difficult to reverse.</p>\n</details>\n\n<details>\n  <summary>How quickly will the bank freeze the company account?</summary>\n  <p>Most major UK banks freeze company accounts within 24 hours of the winding-up petition appearing in the London Gazette. Some banks act even faster through automated Gazette monitoring. The freeze is not a legal requirement but a risk management decision by the bank. Once the account is frozen, a validation order from the court is needed to authorise specific payments.</p>\n</details>\n\n<details>\n  <summary>What is a validation order and how do I get one?</summary>\n  <p>A validation order is a court order under Section 127 of the Insolvency Act 1986 that authorises the company to make specific payments from its bank account despite the petition being in place. Without one, any payment made after the petition date can be voided by the court. You apply to the court with evidence of which payments are essential (wages, rent, key suppliers). A licensed insolvency practitioner or solicitor can prepare and file the application.</p>\n</details>\n\n<details>\n  <summary>What is the difference between a statutory demand and a winding-up petition?</summary>\n  <p>A statutory demand is a formal written notice requiring payment of a debt within 21 days. It is not a court application. A winding-up petition is the next step: a formal application to the court to force the company into compulsory liquidation. The statutory demand is the warning. The petition is the action. If you receive a statutory demand, you have 21 days to pay, negotiate, or dispute before a petition can be filed.</p>\n</details>\n\n<details>\n  <summary>Can I still trade after a winding-up petition has been filed?</summary>\n  <p>Technically, the company is not yet in liquidation and trading is not automatically prohibited. However, two risks make continued trading dangerous. First, the bank freeze triggered by the Gazette notice may make it physically impossible to trade. Second, any new debts incurred after the petition date increase your personal exposure to wrongful trading claims if the company is ultimately wound up. Take professional advice before continuing to trade.</p>\n</details>\n\n<details>\n  <summary>What happens to directors in a compulsory liquidation?</summary>\n  <p>In a compulsory liquidation, the Official Receiver conducts a mandatory investigation into the conduct of all directors. This covers the entire period leading up to insolvency. If the investigation finds wrongful trading, fraudulent trading, preference payments, or transactions at undervalue, directors can face personal liability for company debts and disqualification for up to 15 years. The investigation is more formal and less collaborative than in a director-led CVL.</p>\n</details>\n\n<details>\n  <summary>Is a CVL better than compulsory liquidation for directors?</summary>\n  <p>In most cases, yes. A <a href=\"/creditors-voluntary-liquidation-cvl/\">CVL</a> allows directors to choose their own licensed insolvency practitioner, maintain more influence over how assets are realised, and go through a less confrontational investigation process. The investigation still happens, but it is conducted by the chosen IP rather than the Official Receiver. Directors who move to a CVL before a winding-up order is granted generally face less personal exposure than those who are forced into compulsory liquidation.</p>\n</details>\n\n<details>\n  <summary>How much does it cost to defend a winding-up petition?</summary>\n  <p>The cost depends on the defence route. Paying the debt in full costs the debt amount plus the petitioner's legal costs (typically £1,500 to £3,000 for the petition itself). Disputing the petition through a solicitor can cost £2,000 to £10,000 or more depending on complexity. Moving to a CVL typically costs £3,000 to £6,000 plus VAT for a straightforward case, though this varies by company size and complexity. [HUMAN CONFIRMATION NEEDED: verify current typical CVL cost range]</p>\n</details>\n\n<details>\n  <summary>Can HMRC withdraw a winding-up petition?</summary>\n  <p>HMRC can agree to withdraw a petition if the full debt (including costs and interest) is paid, or if a credible time-to-pay arrangement is agreed. HMRC is generally less willing to negotiate once a petition has been filed than at the statutory demand stage. The earlier you engage, the more likely a negotiated outcome. See our detailed guide on <a href=\"/winding-up-petitions/dealing-with-an-hmrc-winding-up-petition/\">HMRC winding-up petitions</a>.</p>\n</details>\n\n<details>\n  <summary>What happens to employees if the company is wound up?</summary>\n  <p>Employees are automatically dismissed when a winding-up order is made. They become preferential creditors for arrears of wages (up to £800), accrued holiday pay, and notice pay. Redundancy payments are not paid from company assets. Instead, employees claim through the Redundancy Payments Service, which is funded by the National Insurance Fund and administered by the Insolvency Service. There are statutory caps on redundancy payments based on age, length of service, and weekly pay limits.</p>\n</details>\n\n\n<h2>Urgent Next Steps</h2>\n\n<p>If you have received a winding-up petition, these are the actions that matter right now:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Today:</strong> Call a licensed insolvency practitioner for a free initial assessment. Do not wait until the weekend or until you have gathered all your paperwork.</li>\n  <li><strong>Today:</strong> Check whether the petition has been advertised in the London Gazette. If it has, your bank account may already be frozen or at immediate risk.</li>\n  <li><strong>This week:</strong> Gather your most recent management accounts, creditor list, and details of the petitioning creditor's claim. Your insolvency practitioner will need these to assess your options.</li>\n  <li><strong>Before the hearing:</strong> Decide on your response route (pay, dispute, negotiate, validation order, or CVL) and ensure you or your representative will appear at the hearing.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>The initial consultation with a licensed insolvency practitioner is free and confidential. It does not commit you to any course of action. What it does is give you a clear picture of where you stand and which options are still open.</p>\n\n<p>Call the Company Debt team today on <strong>0800 074 6757</strong> to speak to a licensed insolvency practitioner. Lines are open 7 days a week.</p>","65614":"<h2>Closing a Limited Company: The Routes, the Costs, and How to Choose</h2>\n\n<p>Closing a limited company is not one process. It is a choice between several routes, and the right one depends almost entirely on whether the company can pay what it owes.</p>\n\n<p>Directors who pick the wrong route risk personal liability, unnecessary cost, or having the process reversed months later. Directors who pick the right one close the company cleanly and move on.</p>\n\n<p>This page covers the four main closure routes, explains how solvency determines which ones are available to you, and walks through the costs, timescales, and trade-offs of each. If you are not sure where your company sits, start with the <a href=\"/insolvency-test/\">insolvency test</a>.</p>\n\n\n<h2>The Main Routes for Closing a Limited Company</h2>\n\n<p>There are four routes used to close the vast majority of UK limited companies. Two are for solvent companies. Two are for insolvent ones.</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Strike-off (voluntary dissolution)</strong> — the cheapest and simplest route, but only available if the company has no debts it cannot pay, no assets worth distributing, and has stopped trading.</li>\n  <li><strong>Members' Voluntary Liquidation (MVL)</strong> — a formal liquidation for solvent companies with assets to distribute, typically used to extract funds tax-efficiently.</li>\n  <li><strong>Creditors' Voluntary Liquidation (CVL)</strong> — the standard route for insolvent companies where the directors choose to close voluntarily rather than wait for creditors to act.</li>\n  <li><strong>Compulsory liquidation</strong> — forced closure by a creditor (usually HMRC) through a court petition. The directors do not control this process.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>The first decision you need to make is whether your company is solvent or insolvent. Everything follows from that.</p>\n\n\n<h2>Solvent or Insolvent: The First Decision</h2>\n\n<p>Before choosing a route, you need to answer one question: can the company pay all of its debts?</p>\n\n<p>UK insolvency law uses two tests:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Cash-flow test</strong> — Can the company pay its debts as they fall due? If invoices, HMRC liabilities, or loan repayments are overdue and there is no realistic way to pay them in the normal course of business, the company fails this test.</li>\n  <li><strong>Balance-sheet test</strong> — Are the company's total liabilities greater than its total assets? Include everything: HMRC debts, Bounce Back Loans, trade creditors, director loan accounts, and any contingent liabilities such as personal guarantees.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Failing either test means the company is insolvent. That rules out strike-off (in most cases) and MVL, and points you toward a CVL or, if creditors act first, compulsory liquidation.</p>\n\n<p>If you are unsure, the <a href=\"/insolvency-test/\">Company Debt insolvency test</a> takes five minutes and gives you a clear answer. Getting this wrong is the most common and most expensive mistake directors make when closing a company.</p>\n\n\n<h2>Strike-Off: When It Works and When It Does Not</h2>\n\n<p>Strike-off is the simplest way to close a company. You file a DS01 form with Companies House, the company name is published in the Gazette, and if nobody objects within two months, the company is dissolved.</p>\n\n<h3>Eligibility</h3>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>The company must not have traded or sold stock in the last three months.</li>\n  <li>It must not have changed its name in the last three months.</li>\n  <li>There must be no outstanding debts the company cannot pay.</li>\n  <li>It must not be subject to a CVA, administrative order, or other formal insolvency procedure.</li>\n  <li>All employees must have been formally terminated.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Process summary</h3>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>File DS01 with Companies House (fee: £10 online).</li>\n  <li>Notify all creditors, employees, shareholders, and pension trustees.</li>\n  <li>Submit final accounts and a Company Tax Return to HMRC.</li>\n  <li>Wait for the Gazette notice and two-month objection window.</li>\n  <li>If no objections, the company is dissolved.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Cost</h3>\n\n<p>The filing fee is £10. Accountancy fees for final accounts and tax returns vary but typically run between £300 and £800. No insolvency practitioner is needed.</p>\n\n<h3>The risk directors underestimate</h3>\n\n<p>If a creditor objects during the Gazette notice period, the strike-off is suspended. HMRC objects frequently when there are unpaid Corporation Tax, VAT, or PAYE liabilities. A Bounce Back Loan lender can also object. If the company is struck off while debts remain, creditors can apply to restore it to the register for up to six years, and the directors face potential personal liability for the debts. This is why strike-off is not a shortcut for companies that owe money. Read more in our <a href=\"/company-strike-off-and-dissolution/\">full guide to strike-off and dissolution</a>.</p>\n\n\n<h2>MVL: For Solvent Companies with Assets to Distribute</h2>\n\n<p>A Members' Voluntary Liquidation is a formal liquidation process for companies that can pay all their debts in full within 12 months. It is most commonly used when a solvent company has significant retained profits or assets and the directors want to extract those funds as a capital distribution rather than as dividends.</p>\n\n<h3>Why directors choose MVL over strike-off</h3>\n\n<p>Capital distributions through an MVL qualify for Business Asset Disposal Relief (formerly Entrepreneurs' Relief), meaning the first £1 million is taxed at 10% rather than at income tax rates. For a company sitting on £50,000 or more in retained profits, the tax saving typically outweighs the liquidation costs.</p>\n\n<h3>Process summary</h3>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>Directors sign a Declaration of Solvency confirming all debts can be paid within 12 months.</li>\n  <li>Shareholders pass a special resolution to wind up the company.</li>\n  <li>A licensed insolvency practitioner is appointed as liquidator.</li>\n  <li>The liquidator settles all debts, distributes remaining assets to shareholders, and files final returns.</li>\n  <li>The company is dissolved.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Cost</h3>\n\n<p>IP fees for an MVL typically range from £2,000 to £5,000 plus VAT, depending on the complexity of the company's affairs. This is on top of accountancy fees for final accounts.</p>\n\n<h3>The critical condition</h3>\n\n<p>The Declaration of Solvency is a legal statement. If the company turns out to be insolvent, the directors who signed it face personal liability and potential disqualification proceedings. Do not sign a Declaration of Solvency unless you are certain the company can pay every debt in full. If there is any doubt, a CVL is the safer route. See our <a href=\"/members-voluntary-liquidation/\">detailed MVL guide</a> for the full process.</p>\n\n\n<h2>CVL: For Companies That Cannot Pay Their Debts</h2>\n\n<p>A Creditors' Voluntary Liquidation is the standard route for closing an insolvent company when the directors decide to act rather than wait for creditors to force the issue. It is the most common formal insolvency procedure for small and medium-sized companies in England and Wales.</p>\n\n<h3>Why a CVL rather than just walking away</h3>\n\n<p>Walking away from an insolvent company does not make the debts disappear. Creditors can still petition to wind the company up compulsorily, HMRC can pursue the directors for unpaid PAYE and VAT, and the Insolvency Service can investigate director conduct going back years. A CVL puts the closure into a controlled, legal framework and demonstrates that the directors acted responsibly.</p>\n\n<h3>Process summary</h3>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>Directors appoint a licensed insolvency practitioner.</li>\n  <li>The IP prepares a Statement of Affairs.</li>\n  <li>Shareholders pass a resolution to wind up.</li>\n  <li>A decision procedure is held for creditors.</li>\n  <li>The IP realises company assets and distributes proceeds to creditors in statutory order.</li>\n  <li>The company is dissolved.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Director redundancy</h3>\n\n<p>Directors who are employees of the company (on payroll, with an employment contract) may be eligible to claim redundancy pay from the Redundancy Payments Service. This can be worth up to £21,000 and is often used to offset the cost of the liquidation itself. Not every director qualifies. The eligibility criteria are specific, and getting them wrong means a rejected claim. If you think this applies to you, ask the IP to assess eligibility before committing to a route.</p>\n\n<h3>Cost</h3>\n\n<p>CVL costs typically start from around £4,000 to £6,000 plus VAT. The total depends on the size and complexity of the company's affairs, the number of creditors, and whether assets need to be realised. Some IPs offer fixed-fee packages for straightforward cases.</p>\n\n<p>For a full breakdown of the CVL process, costs, and director protections, see our <a href=\"/creditors-voluntary-liquidation-cvl/\">CVL guide</a>.</p>\n\n\n<h2>Compulsory Liquidation: When a Creditor Forces the Issue</h2>\n\n<p>Compulsory liquidation is not a route you choose. It happens when a creditor (most often HMRC) petitions the court to wind up the company because a debt has not been paid.</p>\n\n<p>Once a winding-up petition is presented, the company's bank accounts are typically frozen. The court appoints the Official Receiver to take control of the company's affairs. The directors lose all authority over the business, its assets, and its closure process.</p>\n\n<p>The cost to the company is significantly higher than a voluntary route, and the directors face mandatory conduct investigation by the Official Receiver.</p>\n\n<p>If you have received a winding-up petition or a statutory demand, acting before the court hearing is critical. A CVL started before the petition is heard gives the directors more control, typically results in a better outcome for creditors, and avoids the Official Receiver. Read our <a href=\"/compulsory-liquidation/\">compulsory liquidation guide</a> for a full explanation of the process, timelines, and defence options.</p>\n\n\n<h2>Cost, Speed, and Control: Comparing the Four Routes</h2>\n\n<table>\n  <thead>\n    <tr>\n      <th>Factor</th>\n      <th>Strike-off</th>\n      <th>MVL</th>\n      <th>CVL</th>\n      <th>Compulsory</th>\n    </tr>\n  </thead>\n  <tbody>\n    <tr>\n      <td>Company must be solvent?</td>\n      <td>Yes</td>\n      <td>Yes</td>\n      <td>No (designed for insolvent companies)</td>\n      <td>No (forced by creditor)</td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <td>Typical cost</td>\n      <td>£10 filing + accountant fees</td>\n      <td>£2,000 - £5,000 + VAT (IP fees)</td>\n      <td>£4,000 - £6,000 + VAT (IP fees)</td>\n      <td>£10,000+ (court fees + Official Receiver)</td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <td>Typical timescale</td>\n      <td>3 - 6 months</td>\n      <td>6 - 12 months</td>\n      <td>3 - 6 months (longer if complex)</td>\n      <td>12 - 36 months</td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <td>Director controls the process?</td>\n      <td>Yes</td>\n      <td>Yes (via chosen IP)</td>\n      <td>Yes (via chosen IP)</td>\n      <td>No (Official Receiver)</td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <td>Insolvency practitioner needed?</td>\n      <td>No</td>\n      <td>Yes</td>\n      <td>Yes</td>\n      <td>Yes (appointed by court)</td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <td>Director redundancy available?</td>\n      <td>No</td>\n      <td>No</td>\n      <td>Yes (if eligible)</td>\n      <td>Yes (if eligible)</td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <td>Tax-efficient extraction?</td>\n      <td>Limited (up to £25,000 via capital distribution)</td>\n      <td>Yes (Business Asset Disposal Relief)</td>\n      <td>No</td>\n      <td>No</td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <td>Creditor objection risk?</td>\n      <td>High if debts exist</td>\n      <td>Low (debts paid in full)</td>\n      <td>Low (creditor-approved process)</td>\n      <td>N/A (creditor-initiated)</td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <td>Director conduct investigation?</td>\n      <td>No</td>\n      <td>No</td>\n      <td>IP files report (proportionate)</td>\n      <td>Mandatory (Official Receiver)</td>\n    </tr>\n  </tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>Costs are indicative and vary by provider and case complexity. All figures exclude VAT where stated.</p>\n\n\n<h2>How to Choose the Right Route</h2>\n\n<p>Start with solvency. Everything else follows.</p>\n\n<h3>If the company can pay all its debts</h3>\n\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>No significant assets to distribute?</strong> Strike-off is the cheapest and fastest option. File the DS01, notify creditors, and wait for dissolution.</li>\n  <li><strong>Retained profits above £25,000?</strong> An MVL almost certainly saves more in tax than it costs in IP fees. The capital distribution route via Business Asset Disposal Relief is the main reason directors choose MVL over strike-off.</li>\n  <li><strong>Retained profits under £25,000?</strong> You may be able to take a capital distribution via strike-off without an MVL, but take advice on the tax position first. The £25,000 threshold is not a hard legal rule for every situation.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>If the company cannot pay all its debts</h3>\n\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>No creditor has petitioned yet?</strong> A CVL gives you control. You choose the insolvency practitioner, you set the timeline, and the process demonstrates responsible director conduct. If you qualify for director redundancy, the payout can offset most or all of the cost.</li>\n  <li><strong>A creditor has already petitioned?</strong> You may still be able to start a CVL before the hearing date, but you need to act immediately. Call an insolvency practitioner today, not next week. See our <a href=\"/compulsory-liquidation/\">compulsory liquidation guide</a> for the timeline and defence options.</li>\n  <li><strong>The company might be rescuable?</strong> If the business is viable but carrying legacy debt, a CVA (Company Voluntary Arrangement) or administration may be worth exploring before committing to closure. These are rescue routes, not closure routes, and they require a fundamentally different conversation with an IP.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>If you are not sure about solvency</h3>\n\n<p>Do not guess. An insolvent company dissolved via strike-off can be restored to the register. A Declaration of Solvency signed for an MVL when the company is actually insolvent creates personal liability. Take the <a href=\"/insolvency-test/\">insolvency test</a> or speak to a licensed insolvency practitioner before committing to any route.</p>\n\n\n<h2>Common Mistakes When Closing a Company</h2>\n\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Using strike-off to avoid paying creditors.</strong> Creditors (especially HMRC) object to strike-off applications when debts are outstanding. Even if the company is dissolved, it can be restored to the register for up to six years. Strike-off is for companies with no debts, not for companies trying to escape them.</li>\n\n  <li><strong>Signing a Declaration of Solvency without proper due diligence.</strong> This is a legal statement. If the company later turns out to be insolvent, the directors who signed it face personal liability. Check every liability, including contingent ones, before signing.</li>\n\n  <li><strong>Waiting too long to start a CVL.</strong> The longer an insolvent company continues trading, the greater the risk of wrongful trading claims against the directors. Once you know the company cannot pay its debts, delaying the decision does not improve the outcome. It worsens it.</li>\n\n  <li><strong>Not claiming director redundancy.</strong> Many directors do not realise they may qualify for redundancy pay if they are on the company payroll. This is not automatic and must be claimed through the correct process, but it can be worth up to £21,000 and often covers the cost of the CVL.</li>\n\n  <li><strong>Choosing the cheapest route rather than the correct one.</strong> Strike-off costs £10. A CVL costs thousands. But using strike-off when the company is insolvent can result in personal liability, restoration to the register, and higher costs later. The correct route is the one that matches the company's financial position, not the one with the lowest upfront fee.</li>\n\n  <li><strong>Ignoring HMRC correspondence.</strong> HMRC is the most common petitioning creditor for compulsory liquidation. Statutory demands and winding-up petitions have strict response deadlines. Missing them removes options that were available days earlier.</li>\n</ul>\n\n\n<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>\n\n<details>\n  <summary>Can I close a company with debts?</summary>\n  <p>Yes, but not through strike-off. If the company has debts it cannot pay, the appropriate route is usually a Creditors' Voluntary Liquidation (CVL). This is a formal insolvency process where a licensed insolvency practitioner takes control of the closure, realises any assets, and distributes proceeds to creditors. The company is dissolved at the end of the process, and the debts are written off against the company, not the directors personally (unless personal guarantees are involved). See our <a href=\"/creditors-voluntary-liquidation-cvl/\">CVL guide</a> for the full process.</p>\n</details>\n\n<details>\n  <summary>How much does it cost to close a limited company?</summary>\n  <p>It depends entirely on the route. Strike-off costs £10 in filing fees plus accountant costs for final returns. An MVL typically costs £2,000 to £5,000 plus VAT in insolvency practitioner fees. A CVL typically costs £4,000 to £6,000 plus VAT. Compulsory liquidation costs the company £10,000 or more and is not controlled by the directors. If you are eligible for director redundancy through a CVL, the payout (up to £21,000) can offset most or all of the cost.</p>\n</details>\n\n<details>\n  <summary>How long does it take to close a company?</summary>\n  <p>Strike-off takes three to six months from filing to dissolution. An MVL takes six to twelve months, sometimes longer if assets are complex. A CVL typically completes the main process within three to six months, though the formal dissolution can take longer. Compulsory liquidation is the slowest route, often taking one to three years because the Official Receiver works across a large caseload.</p>\n</details>\n\n<details>\n  <summary>What is the difference between strike-off and liquidation?</summary>\n  <p>Strike-off is an administrative process through Companies House. It is cheap and simple but only works for solvent companies with no significant assets. Liquidation (whether MVL, CVL, or compulsory) is a formal legal process overseen by a licensed insolvency practitioner. It handles debts, distributes assets, and provides legal closure. The key difference: strike-off does not deal with debts or creditors. If the company owes money, strike-off is not the right route. See our <a href=\"/liquidation/\">liquidation overview</a> for a full comparison.</p>\n</details>\n\n<details>\n  <summary>What happens to company debts when a company is dissolved?</summary>\n  <p>Debts owed by the company are written off against the company when it is dissolved through a formal liquidation process (MVL, CVL, or compulsory). However, any debts with personal guarantees survive the company's closure and remain the director's personal responsibility. HMRC can also pursue directors personally for unpaid PAYE and National Insurance in some circumstances. If the company is dissolved via strike-off while debts remain unpaid, creditors can apply to restore it to the Companies House register.</p>\n</details>\n\n<details>\n  <summary>Am I personally liable for company debts?</summary>\n  <p>In most cases, a director's liability is limited to the amount unpaid on their shares. But there are important exceptions. Personal guarantees (common with bank loans, leases, and Bounce Back Loans) make the director personally liable for that specific debt regardless of the company's status. Directors can also face personal liability for wrongful trading if they allowed the company to continue trading while insolvent, or for misfeasance if company assets were misused. A properly conducted CVL reduces, but does not eliminate, the risk of personal claims.</p>\n</details>\n\n<details>\n  <summary>Can I claim redundancy if I am a director?</summary>\n  <p>Potentially, yes. If you are on the company payroll with an employment contract, pay yourself through PAYE, and work regular hours for the company, you may qualify for redundancy pay from the Redundancy Payments Service when the company enters liquidation. The maximum statutory redundancy payout is currently around £21,000, depending on age and length of service. Not every director qualifies. The criteria relate to your employment status, not your directorship. Ask your insolvency practitioner to assess your eligibility before choosing a closure route.</p>\n</details>\n\n<details>\n  <summary>Can HMRC object to my company being struck off?</summary>\n  <p>Yes. HMRC is the most common objector to strike-off applications. If the company has outstanding Corporation Tax, VAT, or PAYE liabilities, HMRC will typically object during the two-month Gazette notice period. This suspends the strike-off process. The company remains on the register, the debts remain, and the directors are back where they started, except that HMRC now knows the company was trying to close without paying. If you suspect HMRC is owed money, do not file for strike-off until you have confirmed the position.</p>\n</details>\n\n<details>\n  <summary>What happens if I do nothing and just leave the company dormant?</summary>\n  <p>The company remains on the Companies House register, and you remain a director with ongoing legal obligations. You must still file annual accounts, a confirmation statement, and Company Tax Returns. Failure to file results in penalties and, eventually, Companies House may strike the company off the register. But creditors can still pursue the company and its directors during that time. HMRC debts accrue interest and penalties. Leaving an insolvent company dormant does not make the debts go away. It typically makes the situation worse and more expensive to resolve later.</p>\n</details>\n\n<details>\n  <summary>Should I speak to an insolvency practitioner before choosing a route?</summary>\n  <p>If there is any possibility the company is insolvent, yes. An initial consultation with a licensed insolvency practitioner is typically free, confidential, and without obligation. The IP can assess the company's financial position, confirm which routes are available, and explain the implications of each. For solvent companies with no debts, your accountant can usually handle the strike-off or refer you for an MVL. For anything involving unpaid debts, creditor pressure, or uncertainty about solvency, professional insolvency advice is not optional. It is how you avoid the mistakes listed above.</p>\n</details>\n\n\n<h2>Next Steps</h2>\n\n<p>If you are closing a limited company, the first step is always the same: confirm whether the company is solvent or insolvent.</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Take the <a href=\"/insolvency-test/\">free insolvency test</a></strong> — five minutes, no obligation, and it tells you which routes are available.</li>\n  <li><strong>Call for a free options review</strong> — speak to a licensed insolvency practitioner who can assess your company's position and explain the costs, timescales, and implications of each route. The call is confidential and does not commit you to anything.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>The longer you wait, the fewer options remain open. If the company is insolvent and a creditor petitions first, you lose the ability to choose your own insolvency practitioner and control the process. Acting now keeps your options open.</p>","77278":"<h2>Company Strike Off and Dissolution: When It Works, When It Backfires</h2>\n\n<p>Striking off a company costs £10. Liquidation costs thousands. That price gap is why most directors searching for a way out land here first.</p>\n\n<p>But strike-off only works cleanly when the company has no debts, no outstanding HMRC liabilities, and no creditors who might object. If any of those apply, the £10 filing fee is not the real cost. The real cost is what happens six months later when HMRC objects, restores the company to the register, and you are back where you started with additional penalties attached.</p>\n\n<p>This page covers who strike-off actually works for, the step-by-step process, and the specific situations where it creates more problems than it solves. If your company owes money to HMRC, holds a Bounce Back Loan, or has unpaid creditors, read the risks section before filing anything.</p>\n\n\n<h2>When Strike-Off Is the Right Route</h2>\n\n<p>Strike-off (formally called voluntary dissolution) suits companies that have genuinely finished trading and have nothing left to settle. That means:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>No outstanding debts to any creditor, including HMRC, suppliers, landlords, and lenders</li>\n  <li>No active or threatened legal proceedings against the company</li>\n  <li>No trading activity in the last three months</li>\n  <li>No name change in the last three months</li>\n  <li>Not currently subject to a Company Voluntary Arrangement or in administration</li>\n  <li>No assets above £25,000 (the capital distribution limit before requiring a formal distribution process)</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>If all of those conditions hold, strike-off is straightforward, inexpensive, and the correct route. You file a DS01 form, notify the right parties, and wait for Companies House to dissolve the company after the statutory notice period.</p>\n\n<p>The typical director this works for: a contractor whose limited company is no longer needed, a side project that never gained traction, or a dormant company that has fulfilled all its obligations. No drama, no creditors, no loose ends.</p>\n\n\n<h2>When Strike-Off Is NOT the Right Route</h2>\n\n<p>This is where the £10 exit becomes expensive. Strike-off is not a debt elimination tool. If you use it to walk away from debts, the debts do not disappear. They follow a different path, and that path usually leads back to you.</p>\n\n<p><strong>You owe money to HMRC.</strong> HMRC monitors the Gazette for strike-off notices. If the company has unpaid Corporation Tax, VAT, or PAYE, HMRC will object and the dissolution is suspended. This is not a theoretical risk. HMRC objections are the single most common reason strike-off applications fail.</p>\n\n<p><strong>You have an outstanding Bounce Back Loan.</strong> The BBL lender will be notified via the Gazette notice. Most lenders will object. Even if the objection is delayed and the company dissolves, the lender can apply to have the company restored to the register for up to six years. The loan does not vanish.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Creditors are chasing payment.</strong> Any creditor who spots the Gazette notice can file an objection with Companies House. A single objection halts the process. Worse, attempting to dissolve a company to avoid paying creditors can be treated as misconduct and may result in director disqualification proceedings.</p>\n\n<p><strong>You have employees.</strong> Strike-off does not trigger redundancy through the National Insurance Fund. If employees are owed wages or redundancy pay, dissolving the company without a formal insolvency process may leave them without the statutory protections they are entitled to. This has consequences for directors, too. See the <a href=\"#employees\">employees section</a> below.</p>\n\n<p><strong>The company has significant assets.</strong> Any assets remaining when the company is dissolved pass to the Crown as bona vacantia. Bank balances, property, equipment, intellectual property: all of it. You cannot reclaim it without applying to restore the company, which costs far more than distributing assets properly would have.</p>\n\n\n<h2>How to Strike Off a Company Step by Step</h2>\n\n<p>If your company qualifies (no debts, no disputes, no loose ends), here is the process:</p>\n\n<h3>Step 1: Board resolution</h3>\n\n<p>A majority of directors must agree to apply for strike-off. This is a formal board resolution. If you are the sole director, you make the resolution yourself, but you still need to document it.</p>\n\n<h3>Step 2: File form DS01 with Companies House</h3>\n\n<p>The DS01 is the application to strike off and dissolve the company. It must be signed by a majority of directors. The filing fee is £10 online or £44 by post. Filing online through the Companies House WebFiling service is faster and cheaper.</p>\n\n<h3>Step 3: Notify all interested parties within seven days</h3>\n\n<p>Within seven days of submitting the DS01, you must send a copy to everyone who could be affected. The law is specific about who must be notified:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>All shareholders (members) who did not sign the application</li>\n  <li>All directors who did not sign the application</li>\n  <li>Any creditors (including HMRC, banks, suppliers, and pension trustees)</li>\n  <li>Any employees or former employees with outstanding claims</li>\n  <li>Any managers or trustees of employee pension funds</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Skipping this notification step is a legal requirement under the Companies Act 2006, not a suggestion. Failure to notify is an offence.</p>\n\n<h3>Step 4: Companies House publishes a Gazette notice</h3>\n\n<p>Once the DS01 is accepted, Companies House publishes a first Gazette notice in The Gazette. This starts a two-month objection window. Any creditor, shareholder, or interested party can object during this period.</p>\n\n<h3>Step 5: If no objections, the company is dissolved</h3>\n\n<p>If nobody objects within two months, Companies House publishes a second notice confirming that the company has been struck off the register and dissolved. The company ceases to exist as a legal entity.</p>\n\n\n<h2>What Documents and Approvals Are Needed</h2>\n\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>DS01 form</strong> — signed by a majority of directors. Available on the Companies House website.</li>\n  <li><strong>Board resolution</strong> — documented agreement from the directors to apply for strike-off.</li>\n  <li><strong>Up-to-date accounts filed with Companies House</strong> — outstanding confirmation statements or accounts can delay or block the application.</li>\n  <li><strong>Final Corporation Tax return</strong> — notify HMRC that the company has ceased trading and file the final CT600 within 12 months of the last accounting period end date.</li>\n  <li><strong>VAT deregistration</strong> — if the company is VAT registered, you must deregister before or alongside the strike-off application.</li>\n  <li><strong>PAYE scheme closure</strong> — if the company runs a payroll, close the PAYE scheme with HMRC.</li>\n  <li><strong>Notification letters</strong> — copies of the DS01 sent to all required parties within seven days.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Missing any of these creates grounds for HMRC to object. The most common delay is unfiled accounts or an open VAT registration.</p>\n\n\n<h2>How Long Strike-Off Takes</h2>\n\n<p>From filing the DS01 to final dissolution, the minimum timeline is approximately three months:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>DS01 processing by Companies House:</strong> typically 2-4 weeks</li>\n  <li><strong>First Gazette notice published:</strong> starts the two-month objection window</li>\n  <li><strong>Two-month objection period:</strong> 8 weeks minimum</li>\n  <li><strong>Second Gazette notice and dissolution:</strong> usually within 1-2 weeks after the objection period closes</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>In practice, allow three to four months with no complications. If HMRC objects (because of unfiled returns, outstanding tax, or an open VAT registration), the process stalls until the issue is resolved. Some directors spend six months or longer going back and forth with HMRC before the strike-off can proceed.</p>\n\n<p>If speed matters and the company has debts, a <a href=\"/creditors-voluntary-liquidation-cvl/\">Creditors' Voluntary Liquidation (CVL)</a> can resolve everything in a more structured timeline with a licensed insolvency practitioner managing creditor communications.</p>\n\n\n<h2>What Strike-Off Costs</h2>\n\n<p>The headline cost is £10 for the online DS01 filing. That is the Companies House fee and nothing more.</p>\n\n<p>But the actual cost of closing a company via strike-off depends on what state the company is in:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Clean company, no debts, all filings current:</strong> £10 (the DS01 fee). This is the genuine cost for a straightforward dissolution.</li>\n  <li><strong>Outstanding accounts or tax returns:</strong> accountant fees to prepare and file these before strike-off can proceed. Budget £300-£1,000+ depending on how far behind the filings are.</li>\n  <li><strong>Informal creditor settlements:</strong> if you need to negotiate settlements with creditors before applying, the cost depends entirely on what is owed.</li>\n  <li><strong>Getting it wrong:</strong> if HMRC restores the company, you face the original debt plus penalties, plus the cost of the restoration application (court fees start at £280 for a third party application), plus any professional fees to deal with the aftermath.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>The £10 figure only applies to the filing. If the company has any complications at all, the total cost of achieving a clean strike-off is higher. And if strike-off fails because debts were unresolved, the eventual cost of formal liquidation plus the wasted time and penalties will be significantly more than if you had gone straight to a CVL.</p>\n\n\n<h2>What Happens to Debts, Assets, and Bank Accounts</h2>\n\n<p>This is the section that matters most if you are considering strike-off to escape debts. It does not work the way many directors hope.</p>\n\n<h3>Debts</h3>\n\n<p>Company debts are not written off by dissolution. If the company is dissolved while debts remain outstanding, creditors have the right to apply for the company's restoration to the register. HMRC can do this for up to 20 years. Other creditors can apply within six years. Once restored, the company exists again, the debts are still owed, and the director is in a worse position than before.</p>\n\n<p>Personal guarantees survive dissolution entirely. If you personally guaranteed a Bounce Back Loan, a commercial lease, or a supplier account, dissolving the company does not affect the guarantee. The creditor pursues you directly.</p>\n\n<h3>Assets</h3>\n\n<p>Any assets owned by the company at the time of dissolution become bona vacantia, meaning they pass to the Crown. This includes bank account balances, property, vehicles, intellectual property, and any debts owed to the company.</p>\n\n<p>If assets above £25,000 were distributed to shareholders before dissolution without following the proper Members' Voluntary Liquidation process, this may be treated as an income distribution rather than a capital distribution. The tax difference is substantial.</p>\n\n<h3>Bank accounts</h3>\n\n<p>Most banks freeze the company account once the first Gazette notice is published. Any remaining balance passes to the Crown as bona vacantia after dissolution. If you need to access those funds, you must apply to the Treasury Solicitor (or the relevant Crown body in Scotland or Northern Ireland) or apply for the company to be restored. Both processes involve cost and delay.</p>\n\n\n<h2>Risks of Getting Strike-Off Wrong</h2>\n\n<p>Directors who use strike-off to sidestep debts face a specific set of risks. These are not hypothetical.</p>\n\n<p><strong>HMRC restoration.</strong> HMRC can apply to restore a dissolved company to the register if tax is owed. Once restored, all tax debts, interest, and penalties are live again. HMRC uses this power routinely, particularly for VAT and Corporation Tax debts.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Personal liability.</strong> If a director caused the company to dispose of assets or make payments to avoid creditors before strike-off, that behaviour can be investigated. Under the Insolvency Act, transactions at an undervalue and preferences made in the lead-up to insolvency can be challenged. Directors can be held personally liable for losses caused to creditors.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Director disqualification.</strong> Attempting to dissolve a company to avoid debts is a factor the Insolvency Service considers in disqualification proceedings. A disqualification order bans you from acting as a director for 2 to 15 years.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Bounce Back Loan investigations.</strong> The government has funded dedicated investigation resources for BBL fraud and misuse. Dissolving a company with an outstanding BBL without following a formal insolvency process attracts scrutiny. A licensed insolvency practitioner handling a CVL provides a structured, transparent process that demonstrates you dealt with the loan properly.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Creditor restoration.</strong> Any creditor owed money can apply to the court to restore the company within six years of dissolution. The director has no control over this. The creditor bears the application cost, but if successful, the company is restored and the debts are enforceable again.</p>\n\n\n<h2 id=\"employees\">Employees and Strike-Off</h2>\n\n<p>If the company has employees at the time of strike-off, those employees lose access to statutory redundancy protections that would otherwise be available through a formal insolvency process.</p>\n\n<p>In a <a href=\"/creditors-voluntary-liquidation-cvl/\">CVL</a>, employees are made redundant by the liquidator and can claim statutory redundancy pay, unpaid wages, holiday pay, and notice pay from the National Insurance Fund (the Redundancy Payments Service). These claims are processed relatively quickly, and in many cases the redundancy payments are substantial enough to offset a significant portion of the liquidation costs.</p>\n\n<p>In a strike-off, none of that applies. There is no formal insolvency event, so the Redundancy Payments Service has no basis to pay out. Employees are left to pursue their claims directly against the directors, which is more expensive and less certain for everyone involved.</p>\n\n<p>If you have employees and the company cannot pay what it owes them, strike-off is the wrong route. A CVL protects the employees and, through the redundancy offset, can reduce the net cost of liquidation significantly.</p>\n\n\n<h2>Alternatives: When Liquidation Is the Better Route</h2>\n\n<p>If your company has debts it cannot pay, the correct formal process is a <a href=\"/creditors-voluntary-liquidation-cvl/\">Creditors' Voluntary Liquidation (CVL)</a>. This is the route designed for insolvent companies.</p>\n\n<p>A CVL costs more than £10. Typical fees range from £3,000 to £6,000+ depending on the complexity of the case. That figure stops many directors from considering it. But the comparison is misleading for three reasons:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Redundancy offset.</strong> If the company has employees (including working directors on PAYE), the statutory redundancy pay claimed through the National Insurance Fund can offset a large portion of the liquidation cost. In some cases, the redundancy payment exceeds the liquidation fee. This is the single most important factor that directors researching strike-off tend to miss. <a href=\"/liquidation/\">Check whether you qualify.</a></li>\n\n  <li><strong>Debt resolution is final.</strong> A CVL formally deals with all creditors. Once the liquidation is complete, there is no six-year window for creditors to restore the company. The company is dissolved, the debts are handled, and you move on without looking over your shoulder.</li>\n\n  <li><strong>Director protection.</strong> Acting responsibly by placing an insolvent company into formal liquidation demonstrates that you took your duties seriously. It is the opposite of the behaviour that triggers disqualification proceedings. Directors who take proper advice and follow the formal process are treated very differently from directors who tried to dissolve the company quietly.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Strike-off is the right route for solvent companies with nothing left to settle. For companies with debts, a CVL is not the expensive alternative. It is the route that actually resolves the situation. <a href=\"/closing-a-limited-company/\">Compare all your options for closing a limited company.</a></p>\n\n<p><strong>Not sure whether your company is insolvent?</strong> Use the <a href=\"/insolvency-test/\">free insolvency test</a> to check your position before deciding on a route.</p>\n\n<p><em>Company Debt provides licensed insolvency practitioner services including CVLs. The comparison above reflects our editorial assessment, but we have a commercial interest in formal liquidation. If strike-off is the right route for your company, we will tell you that on a free call.</em></p>\n\n\n<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>\n\n<details>\n  <summary>Can I strike off a company with debts?</summary>\n  <p>You can file the DS01 form, but any creditor (including HMRC) can object and halt the process. Even if the company is dissolved with debts outstanding, creditors can apply to restore it to the register for up to six years (HMRC for up to 20 years). Strike-off does not eliminate debts. If the company is insolvent, a <a href=\"/creditors-voluntary-liquidation-cvl/\">CVL</a> is the formal route for dealing with those debts properly.</p>\n</details>\n\n<details>\n  <summary>How much does it cost to strike off a company?</summary>\n  <p>The Companies House filing fee is £10 online (£44 by post). That is the direct cost. If you have outstanding accounts, tax returns, or a VAT registration to close, the total cost will include accountant fees to resolve those. For a clean company with no loose ends, £10 is the genuine total.</p>\n</details>\n\n<details>\n  <summary>How long does company strike-off take?</summary>\n  <p>Minimum three months from filing the DS01 to dissolution. Companies House processing takes 2-4 weeks, then there is a mandatory two-month Gazette notice period. If HMRC or a creditor objects, the timeline extends until the issue is resolved, which can take six months or longer.</p>\n</details>\n\n<details>\n  <summary>What happens to a Bounce Back Loan if the company is struck off?</summary>\n  <p>The loan does not disappear. The lender can object to the strike-off, or apply to restore the company to the register after dissolution. If you personally guaranteed the loan (which is not standard for BBLs but applies to some), the creditor can pursue you directly. Using a CVL to deal with a BBL provides a formal, transparent resolution that a strike-off does not.</p>\n</details>\n\n<details>\n  <summary>Can HMRC object to strike-off?</summary>\n  <p>Yes, and they do so frequently. HMRC monitors Gazette notices and objects if the company has outstanding Corporation Tax, VAT, PAYE, or unfiled returns. An HMRC objection suspends the dissolution until the tax position is cleared. This is the most common reason strike-off applications fail.</p>\n</details>\n\n<details>\n  <summary>What happens to the company bank account after strike-off?</summary>\n  <p>Most banks freeze the account when the Gazette notice is published. Any remaining balance passes to the Crown as bona vacantia after dissolution. To recover funds, you must either apply to the Treasury Solicitor or apply to restore the company, both of which involve cost, paperwork, and delay.</p>\n</details>\n\n<details>\n  <summary>Can a struck-off company be restored?</summary>\n  <p>Yes. A company can be restored to the register through an administrative restoration (by the former directors) or a court order (by a creditor, shareholder, or other interested party). Creditors have six years. HMRC has up to 20 years. Once restored, the company exists again as if it had never been dissolved, and all debts are enforceable.</p>\n</details>\n\n<details>\n  <summary>Do I still need to file accounts and tax returns during strike-off?</summary>\n  <p>Yes. Until the company is formally dissolved, your filing obligations continue. You must file a final set of accounts with Companies House and a final Corporation Tax return with HMRC. Outstanding filings are one of the most common triggers for HMRC objections.</p>\n</details>\n\n<details>\n  <summary>What is bona vacantia?</summary>\n  <p>Bona vacantia means \"ownerless goods.\" When a company is dissolved, any assets it still owns pass to the Crown. This includes bank balances, property, vehicles, intellectual property, and debts owed to the company. The Treasury Solicitor manages bona vacantia assets in England and Wales. Recovering assets from the Crown is possible but involves a formal application process and is not guaranteed.</p>\n</details>\n\n<details>\n  <summary>Is strike-off the same as liquidation?</summary>\n  <p>No. Strike-off is an administrative process for closing a solvent company that has stopped trading. Liquidation is a formal insolvency process managed by a licensed insolvency practitioner. Liquidation deals with creditors, distributes assets, investigates director conduct, and provides statutory protections for employees. Strike-off does none of these things. If the company has debts, liquidation is the appropriate route.</p>\n</details>\n\n\n<h2>Next Steps</h2>\n\n<p>If your company has no debts, no outstanding HMRC liabilities, and no creditors who might object, strike-off is the right route. File the DS01, notify all parties, and allow three to four months for the process to complete.</p>\n\n<p>If your company has debts, do not file a DS01. The risks of HMRC restoration, personal liability, and creditor action are real and well-documented. Get a clear picture of your position first:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Check whether you are insolvent:</strong> <a href=\"/insolvency-test/\">Take the free insolvency test</a></li>\n  <li><strong>Understand the CVL process and costs:</strong> <a href=\"/creditors-voluntary-liquidation-cvl/\">Creditors' Voluntary Liquidation explained</a></li>\n  <li><strong>Find out if redundancy offsets the cost:</strong> Call the Company Debt team for a free, confidential assessment. If strike-off is the right route for your situation, that is what we will recommend.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>The worst outcome is filing for strike-off, having it fail, and then paying for liquidation anyway with added penalties and lost time. If there is any doubt about debts, get advice before you file.</p>"};window.__pagesReady=true;